{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_appling_ver02/data/sn82007642/00279558194/1930111301/0792.xml":{"full_text":"EIGHT\nLOCAL AFFAIRS\nDr. and Mrs. Fred Hodges are\nmoving this week into an apartment\nin the Cook home on Main Street-\nMiss Louise Critcher spent last\nweek-end with Mr. and Mrs- Clyde\nRitch in Greensboro, N. C.\nDr. and Mrs. J- M. Gaither are\nspending the week in Atlanta, where\nthe doctor is transacting business-\nMrs. James Moore will entertain\nthe Maids and Matrons Club on Sat-i\nurday night, November 15th. at 7:45\nn- m.\nMr. and Mrs. Ernest Comer, of\nGreensboro, were guests of Dr. and\nMrs- G. K. Moose during the first\nof this week.\nMl. Wilej H. Swift, prominent\nGreensboro attorney, is spending a\nfew days visiting with home folks in\nthis county.\nThere will be a meeting of the lo\ncal Parent-Teacher Association a*,\nthe Demonstration School building\nThursday afternoon at o\u2019clock- A\nfull attendance is urged.\nCitizens of North Carolina, open\nyour hearts and loosen your purse\nstrings to the Orphan Homes of the\nState at Thanksgiving this year to a\ngreater degree than you have ever\ndone before. The need is urgent.\nMr. G. C. Greer and family, of\nZionville. left Saturday for Patton,\nCalif., where they will spend the win\nter with their sons. Messrs. Ralph and\nTheodore, who have been citizens ot\nCalifornia for several years-\nMrs. Kay Boatwright, who has\nbeen visiting her parents, Mr. and\nMrs. John W. Hodges, for a few\ndays, left Sunday to join Dr. Boat\nwright in Kingsport, Tenn.. where\nthey will make their home this win\nter.\nMrs. ,J. A. Williams gave a very\nentertaining talk on \u201cFrance and the\nArmistice\u201d Tuesday morning to Mr.\nHowell\u2019s seventh grave class in the\ngraded school. Trophies gathered in\nEurope by Mrs. Williams on her re\ncent tour were also exhibited-\nThe Democrat is grieved to learn\nthat Miss Eva Brown of Neva, Tenn\nelder sister of the late Captain B. K.\nBrown of Shouns\u2014now 92 years of\nage\u2014sustained a fall some days ago,\nand her condition since has been con\nsidered very serious.\nRev. C. C. McKaraher. wife and\nson, of Cedarville, N. J-. visited with\nfriends in this vicinity during the\npast week. The reverend gentleman\nwas formerly engaged in church work\nat Shulls Mills and has many friends\nlocally who welcome his brief, vis\nits.\nRev. and Mrs. P A. Hicks, Miss\nElizabeth Cowan, Professors J. T.\nWright and Superintendent Smith\nHagaman, of Boone, and Messrs. \\V\nY. Perry. William Farthing and Roy\nDotson, of the Cove Creek section,\nleft Tuesday for the Baptist State\nConvention, in session this week in\nRaleigh-\nMr. -I. Frank Robbins, of the Wild\nwood Nurseries, left yesterday morn\ning for New York and other North\nern cities, as far up as Boston, to\nlook after the interests of his con\ncern, and to book orders for the\nspring trade on evergreens- Mr. j\nRobbins expects to be gone about a\nmonth.\nMr. G. C- Bradley has sold his\npretty property on Route GO, near\nthe corporate limits of the city, to I\na gentleman by the name of Foster i\nfrom Ohio. We are not informed as,\nto the consideration involved, but it;\nis a very valuable location. Mr- Brad\nley is a hustler when it comes to j\ntrading, and has no idea of leaving i\nBoone. So it will be interesting to;\nsee what he will do next.\nMr- Ben Goss, of West Jefferson,!\ndefeated Republican candidate for!\nin Ashe County, was\nin town a few hours Tuesday. He is\na game loser and says, though de\nfeated, he considers his experience!\nthrough the campaign was worth all\nit cost him. A hard fighter and a\ngame loser are two fine attributes in\nany man running for public office\u2014;\nor for the ordinary layman in poli-!\ntics, as far as that goes.\nNot only the Methodists of Boone, I\nbut the people of ail denominations I\nwithin her borders, were delighted;\nover the return of Dr. Chandler to!\nthi scharge for another year. It has!\nbeen said by some that \u201cDr. Chan-;\ndler is too big a preacher for Boone,\nbut it seems the annual conference]\nand the great theologian himself did\nnot so decide, thanks to their fine!\njudgment.\nMiss Louise Hodges, for years a\nvalued member of the selling force\nat the Isaacs Department Store in\nBoone, but in the late summer ac\ncepting an offer from a big business!\nconcern in Mount Airy handling the:\nsame lines, was a week-end visitor to]\nher home, loved ones and friends. I\nShe seems to be delighted with her]\nwork\u2014the only trouble, she says, is i\nthat she cannot have her many Boone\nfriends with her in Mount Airy. AI\ngreat girl, is Louise-\nMr. James Carter has taken the\nAsheville t Citizen mail line from\nSpruce Pine to Boone, the morning\npapers to be delivered here by 8 a.\nm. The edition intended for this\nsection are delivered to him from\nAsheville very early in the morning\nin time for him to make the run on\nschedule. He went on duty this\nmorning.\nMr. Ralph Lyons, manager of the\ndowntown Carolina Store, was exhib\niting a huge tarantula Saturday,\nwhich had been shipped from its\ntropical element in a bunch of ba\nnanas. The great hairy spider,\nshould it have extended its legs,\nWould have been almost as large as\nan ordinary saucer. The venomous\ninsect was turned over to the college\nmuseum.\nNUMBER FOUR\nBorn to Mr- and Mrs. James C.\nRivers, Monday morning, a daughter,\nJimmie Emeline. So, you see, the old\nman of the shop is \u201cgrand-dad\u201d\nagain. This is No. 4, all girls-\nCove Creek Dozen Club Meets\nWith Mrs. Scott Swift.\nA delightful meeting of the Cove]\nCreek Dozen Club was held on Satur-j\nday afternoon with Mrs. Scott Swift\nas hostess at her home at Mabel.\nMrs- Hattie Johnson, president of\nthe club, presided over the meeting.\nA very interesting program on the I\nlife of Kate Douglas Wiggin was ren-j\ndered. After this the hostess engaged\nher guests in a lively contest, \u201cNuts]\nto Crack.\u201d Mrs. Ijattie Johnson]\nproved successful in this and was\nawarded a nut set- Mrs. Stanley Har\nris was the recipient of a box of\nchestnuts, booby prize.\nMrs. Swift, assisted by Mrs. Hat\ntie Johnson, served a delicious salad\ncourse- Besides club members present\nMrs. Selmer Fuller of Mountain City\nand Miss Daisy Mast were guests of\nMrs. Swift.\nFriday Nighters Guests at\nHome of Mrs. Williams\nMrs. Harry Tharrington and Mrs-\nHenry Conrad entertained the Friday\nNighters on Friday night at the home\nof the latter\u2019s mother, Mrs. John\nWilliams.\ni The home was beautifully decorat\nj ed with late autumn flowers and the\nspirit of Halloween was charmingly\ncart ied out by the hostess-\nHalloween contests were given and\nthe prizes won by Mrs. Gene Story\nj and Miss Ellen Coffey. After this de\nlightful refreshments were served by J\nj the hostesses assisted by little Misses i\nLouise Frevette and Man Louise\nWilliams.\nThose present were Mesdames Har-|\nj ry Tharrington, Henry Conrad, Her-i\nI bert Ingle. Stuart Cannon. Gene Sto\nry, Clarence Prevette. Cameron Wil\ni liams. Joe Winkler. Thomas Coffey, j\nJr.. Misses Polly Hayes, Lena Reeves,]\nEllen Coffey and Lucile Reed.\nDELPHIAN CHAPTER HOLDS\nINTERESTING MEETING TUES\nThe Yonahlossee Delphian Chapter\nmet Tuesday afternoon in Miss Bou\nchelle's room at the Demonstration\nSchool. There was a short business\nsession, during which it was decided\ni to use the Demonstration School as]\nthe regular meeting place of the i\nchapter, on the second and fourth\nTuesdays of each month, at 4 p- m.\nThe subject for Tuesday\u2019s lesson\nwas \u201cThe Land of the Pyramids\u201d;\nleader. Mrs. James Moore; Delphian\nTraveler. Miss Eula Todd; \u201cThe\nNile,\u201d Mrs. John Horton: \"Egypt and\nthe Modern Man.\" Mrs. Russell]\nHodges; \"Before the Pyramid Da.vs,\u201d|\nMrs. G. K Moose; \u201cOur Sources of j\nEgyptian History.\u201d Mrs. M. P- Crit\ncher \u201cLife in the Pyramid Age,\"]\nMrs. James Mast; \"The Egyptian\nView of Life.\u201d Miss Elizabeth Ruck\ni er;; lesson summary. Mrs. James\ni Moore.\nAll reports were given in an in\nteresting and concise manner and the\nj whole meeting was thoroughly en\ni joyed by those present.\nHOME ECONOMICS GIRLS OF\nHIGH SCHOOL PRESENT PLAY\nThe home economics girls of the\nBoone High School, under the super\nvision of Miss Dodds, presented a\nvery fitting play and program on\nFriday, November 7th.\nThe evening\u2019s entertainment had a\ni two-l'old purpose\u2014first, to interest\nboth young and old in good foods,\nwhich promote good health; second,\nj to use the proceeds derived from the\nprogram in buying equipment for .be\nkitchen.\nTwo beautiful selections rendered\nby Miss Nell Trivett preceded the\ncurtain raising at S o'clock, display-j\ning a group of fifty-eight girls,!\ndressed in white aprons and caps,]\nwho sang several food songs.\nA trial scene between Milk and\nj Coffee followed. It was interesting!\nj indeed to see Good Food and her\nchildren, who were Milk's witnesses-\nCoffee and Mal-nutrition played their\ni parts well, hut even so, they had too\nfew witnesses.\nA four-act plav entitled \"Punish\nment was cleverly given. The entire\nProgram showed that it had been\nfaithfully worked on for sometime.\nDAVIDSON\u2019S STORE IN BIG\nNINTH ANNIVERSARY EVENT\nIn celebration of the ninth anni-j\nversa ry of its business connection in\nBoone, the Davidson Department!\n-Store opens its doors tomorrow morn- j\nwith a gigantic sale of merchan\ndise. Mr. I. L. Lanier, well-known I\nsales conductor of Charlotte, his son!\ni and nephew, are in charge of the,\nevent, and the entire enormous stock\n<>f. merchandise is included in the\nprice reductions. A two-page adver\ntisement in this issue tells of the spe\n<'ific savings which may be effected\nj by attending the eight-day sale.\nMr- Lanier comes to Boone from\nI Sugar Grove when he has been en\ngaged in conducting a successful\ni sale for Mr. A. C. Mast\n\nTHE WEATHER\nI Weather report for week ending\nj November Bth, as compiled by the\nCo-operative Station, Appalachian\nI State Teachers College, Boone, J. T.\nC. Wright, observe\nAverage maximum temperature,\nI -\u201856 degrees.\nAverage minimum temperature, 21\nf degrees\nAverage daily range in tempera\nture, 19 degrees-\nGreatest daily range in tempera\nture, 29 degrees; date Bth.\nAverage temperature at 6 p. m.\n(time of observation), 33 degrees.\nHighest temperature reached, 45\ndegrees; date 3rd.\nLowest temperature reached, 12\ndegrees; date 2nd-\nNumber inches of rainfall( includ\ning melted snow), 0.64.\nNumber inches of snowfall, 3.25.\nGreatest rainfall in 24 hours, 0-54;\ndate, 4th.\nNumber of days with 0.01 inch or\nmore rainfall, 2.\nNumber of clear days, 4.\nNumber of cloudy days, 1.\nNumber of partly cloudy days,- 2.\nDirection of prevailing wind, south\neast-\nDates of heavy frost, 2nd, 3rd, Bth.\nDates of light frost, 7th.\nOther phenomena described as fol\nlows: Lunar halo on 2nd and 6th;\nsolar halo on 3rd.\nTHE WATAUGA DEMOCRAT \u2014EVERY THURSDAY\u2014BOONE, N. C.\nfrom Our FatlyFiJen\nItems from The Democrat of\nNovember 12, 1891\nTen more dwellings will he built\nin Blowing Rock this winter- This 1\nI sounds like business.\nJ. F. Hardin started last Monday\nfor the Southern Market with anoth\ner good load of beef cattle.\nDr. J. C. Blair, of Lenoir, was\npresent at the burial of his father,\nHenry Blair, on last Monday-\nOwing to the high water on Tues-\nday evening the mails failed to reach\nBoone from Flk Park and Jefferson.\nThe County Commissioners have\ndecided to make a lord instead of a\nbridge across the river on Middle\nFork Road.\nThat esteemed gentleman, J. E-\nFinley, has moved from his home on\nMeat Camp to North \\V ilkesboro.\nwhere he anticipates going into busi\nness.\nCaptain -J. C. McGhee and two sons\nare at work on tho chimneys of R. L.\nCount-ill's new dwelling. Dick will\nsoon he the occupant of one of the\nneatest and best arranged houses in\nthe county.\nThe marriage of Colonel Todd to\nMrs- Edmisten took us by surprise.\nHe conducted his courtship very\nshrewdly to keep anyone from know\ning. or even suspecting, matrimonial\nProduce Is Sought for\nAdvent Church School\nRev. Luther Troxwell, president ot j\nthe Adventist Christian Seminary.]\nBridgeport, Ala., is expected to visit i\nWith the local church on the fifth]\nSunday. The minister will make the,\nI trip by motor truck and a movement]\nhas been successfully begun to load]\nthe- vehicle with much-needed edibles\nfor the return trip. Several citizens j\nof the community have voluntarily\noffered potatoes, canned fruit, etc.,\nland it is hoped that the truck will he]\nloaded to capacity with good whole-]\nsome food for the worthy institu-j\ntion. Anyone wishing to make a con-\ntribution even though it is only one\njar of canned fruit, or a few pota\ntoes, please get in touch with Mr. V.'-]\nH Gragg. Boone, N. C.\n\u201cSandy\u201d Graham May\nBe Candidate in 1936\n(Special to The Democrat)\nRaleigh, N- C. \u2014A. H. (Sandy)\nGraham, of Hillsboro, is expected to\nhe a candidate for Lieutenant Gover\nnor of North Carolina in 1932, and;\nfor Governor of North Carolina in]\n1936-\nWhile no definite announcement j\nhas been made in either case, it is\ngenerally understood that Mr. Gra-i\nham will enter the race for Lieuten-]\nant Governor in'due time, and that\nsuch entry will have a definite oh-1\nject\u2014that of becoming candidate for)\nGovernor four years later.\nAlthough only forty years old, Mr.\nGraham has packed a lot of experi\nence in his limited years, particular\nly since he graduated from the Uni\nversity of North Carolina in 1912,\nstudied law there the next year and\nat Harvard Law School in 1913-14.\nHe entered tho First Officers Train\ning Camp early in 1917 and served\nfor more than two years, rising to\na captaincy with the 81st Division\nin France.\nSince 1921 he has been a member\nof the General Assembly from Or\nange County and has served as chair\nman of several important commit\ntees, all leading him to the speaker\nship of that body in 1929. He has\nserved as a member of the Advisory\nBudget Commission for several years\nand during the past two months has\nbeen executive counsel to Governor\nGardner, all of which positions, his\nfriends say, are excellent training\nfor the next two positions to which\nhe is almost certain to aspire.\nIn the first contest he will doubt\nless have as an opponent D. F. Giles,\nof Marion, former legislator, now\nsecretar# of the N- C\u2022 Railroad and,\nwithin the past year or two. becom\ning an atttorney at law. William\nF. Wood, also of Marion, and State\nSenator, has also made some sort of\nconditioned\u2019 announcement for the\nLieutenant Governorship.\nIn the second race, that for the\nGovernorship. Mr. Graham will in all\nprobability contend with Judge Tom\nL. Johnson, Asheville, formerly of\nLumberton, who retired from the ap\nproaching 1932 governorship race,\nbi t who has let it be known that he\nstill has his eye on that goal in 1936,\nand Colonel Thomas L. Kirkpatrick,\nCharlotte, original good roads en\nthusiast, who has said he expects to\nhe a candidate in 1936. Other pros\npects are W. M. Hendren, Winston-\nSalem, A- L- Brooks, Greensboro,\nand\u2014but that quintet will he enough\nto mention for the present.\nBIRTHDAY PARTY\nMrs. Clarence Angel delightfully\nentertained a number of the little\nchildren of the communtyi last Sat\nurday afternoon in honor of the fifth\nbirthday of her daughter, Little Amy\nLee. Games were played, refresh\nments served and the little folks\nspent an evening of pleasure long to\nbe remembered.\nBIRTHDAY DINNER\nMiss Grace Edmisten, daughter of\nMr. and Mrs. Dock Edmisten, of\nRutherwood, celebrated her birthday\nanniversary last Sunday when she\nentertained several friends at dinner.\nThe young lady is a senior in high\nschool, and is very popular with a\nlarge circle of friends. Her guests\nenjoyed to the fullest the bountiful\ndinner and wish for her much suc\ncess and happiness-\nJohn Tiger, of Shooting Creek in\nClay County, reports harvesting three\ntons of red clover hay an acre from\nsix acres of land in two cuttings-\nLUMBER! LUMBER!\u2014If you want\ngood Building Lumber or good\nChestnut Shingles, see or write J.\nE. Maltha or S. B. Haves, Vilas,\nN. C. 7-6-4 t\nalliance. Mrs- Edmisten is an excel\nlent lady and we congratulate the\nColonel upon securing such a good\nwife. May happiness attend them\never.\nWe are very sorry to say that our\npopular townsman, James 11. B:.\u00bb*:n, j\nis in Jefferson very ill with intermit-]\ntent fever. He has been traveling a>j\na drummer for some time, and was]\nout in that capacity when he wasi\ntaken sick. Mr. R. L. Councill. his\nbrother-in-law, is visiting him and we|\nmost earnestly hope that he may be,\nable to return to home and friends\nbefore many days.\nOur venerable friend, Henry Blair,\nof New River, died at his home on\nhist Saturday and was buried Mon\nday. Mr. Blair was, we think, near\n86 years of age, and only outlived\nhis wife about one year. His three\nsons. Dr. Blair of Lenoir, E. S. Blair\nof Wilkesboro, C. H. Blair and his\ndaughter. Mrs. William Horton of\nWatauga, survive him. Watauga loses\none of her most prominent and high-1\nly-respeeted citizens in the death of\nthis aged gentleman Few people live I\nlonger than Mr- Blair or have fewer\nenemies. He lived a correct life and I\nspent his last years reading his Bible\nin which he found great consolation.]\nHe had been a member of the- Three];\nForks Baptist Church for many years.:,\nTHEY SLEEP\nBy H. CLAY FERREE\nIn Winston-Salem Journal\nThe salty winds from the Chan\nnel sweep across the long white\nlines of crosses in dear old Pic\nardy. picturesque in its placid calm,\nthe\" Cathedral of Amiens, pointing\nbony fingers to the sky.\nThey sleep- Les neiges d\u2019antan\nhave fallen athwart the poppy field j\nand the wooden crosses are slow\nly rotting around their bases. But\nthe lark still sings in aftergioam,\nand dawn winds soft as Provencal\nmaiden\u2019s smile chant the requiem\nof those who sleep beneath the\nturf.\nThey sleep- Nimble feet of youth j\ncaress the damp earth above their j\nheads, and peasants returning from j\ntheir toil walk slowly among the\ncrosses, now and anon groping for\nthe beads and crucifix. \u201cThey\nsleep,\u201d say they, \"and Mother of j\nGod, for what?\u201d\nThey sleep. In sacred soil where\nonce the bare feet of Jeanne d'Arc\nstrode on to victory and immortal-\nity against the hated Briton, and j\nbathed with her blood that earth\nwhich has become for them the i\nwinding sheet and shroud. In\nyouth's high tide of courage with i\nbeating pulse and leaping heart, j\nthey charged the legions of Attila j\nin a war that was to be the last j\ntribute to greed, the last concession j\nto Mars, the drinker of human\nblood. They sleep, and what say j\nyon sentinels on the frowning j\ntower?\nThey sleep. Men say this and\nthat, and the causes of the war j\nare forgotten in the mad race of j\nnations to prepare for the next\nconflict. Old men may grieve and I\nwidows may weep, and broken j\nmothers mutter of communing with\nthe dead. Children may pause to\nshudder at the ruined towers, and\nto wonder at the sight of many\ngraves. But beyond the loom of\nthe tallest star, they who died live\non, while the dark clouds gather\nand bayonets flash, and powers\nbargain in terms of flesh and blood-\nThey sleep. Perhaps it is just as\nwell that little white crosses are\netched against that sky forever.\nCongress Control Is\nStill Held in Doubt\nWashington.\u2014United in seeking a\nreturn of prosperity, national party\nleaders returned to the business\nmonday of trying to find out who\nwon Congressional control in Tues\nday\u2019s biennial election.\nRepublicans and Democrats both\nwere determined to fight it out to\nthe last vote in the-last precinct and\nit is obvious that the actual control-!\nling party of the next Senate and!\nHouse probably will not be deter\nmined until the closely divided mem\nbership meets a year hence.\nThe final but unofficial returns)\nleft the Republicans with a majority\nof one in both House and in the\nSenate and the leaders were prepared\nto seek control again on these stand\nings. It was entirely possible that\ntwo or three votes in one district\nmight settle the whole issue for the\nHouse.\nBut with the session such a long\nway off, unless a special session is\ni called next spring, it, was agreed on\nall sides that it was too early to\nspeculate. Party chieftains were\nchecking over recounts in more than\na score of closely contested House\nelections.\nMeanwhile, attention returned to\nthe approaching short session which\nwill wind up the business of the old\ni Congress\nTHOSE FUNNY MONICKERS\nThe curious nicknames of the\nMarx Brothers, who will appear on\nthe Pastime Theatre screen Monday\nand Tuesday, November 17-18, iit\ntheir second Paramount talking com\nedy, \u201cAnimal Crackers,\u201d are ex\nplained thus:\nGroucho Marx, who started life as\nJulius, got his name from the dispo\nsition he displayed when approached\nfor a loan\u2014or so his brothers ex\nplain it.\nHarpo really is Arthur, but his per\nformance on the harp won him h;\nstage cognomen.\nI Chico once was Leonard\u2014but he\nbecame fond of poultry.\nZeppo, or Herbert, received his\nname from his brothers who insist\nthat in boyhood he resembled a cir\ncus freak of that name.\nSIX REPUBLICANS\nARE ELECTED TO\nN.C. LEGISLATURE!\n(Continued from Page 1)\n\ndent. Lieutenant Governor Fountain.\nThey are Marvin K. Blount. Green\nville: Rivers D- Johnson, Warsaw,\nand H. P. Horton, Pittsboro, the lat\nj ter two returning after two-year in-\ntervals.\nDeposits in State Banks Decrease\nDeposits in State hanks in North i f\nCarolina decreased nearly ten mil-1:\niion dollars. $9,950,000. during the]:\nnast year, or from $250,000,000 on\nSeptember 24. last, as compared with j\nOctober 4. 1929. the report of John\nMitchell, chief State bank examiner,\non the 405 (tanks, including eighty\nfour branches, shows. j\nTotal resources of these banks de-\ncreased $27,652,000 in that period, j\nor from $341, 182.000 to $313,530.-\n000. hut in the last three months, j;\nsince the call dated June 30, 19.50. j\nthe resources have increased slight-\nly, $1,469,000, the report shows. In-\nvestments in stocks and bonds dur- j\ning the year increased by $5,800,000,\nwhile decreases were shown in loans\nand discounts of $36,000,000. in gov-1 j\neminent securities $1,800,000, in]:\ncash due from hanks of $1,200,000. j\nand in hanking house, furniture and\nfixtures. $4,300,000. Capital, surplus\netc- dropped $2,200,000 and borrowed\nmoney decreased $15,000,000 the re- j\nport shows.\nBoard of Education Has Authority\nA county board of education has\nsupreme and final authority in fix-\ning the number of teachers in eoun-\ntv schools, even at a figure lower j;\nthan the State schedule, the North]]\nCarolina Supreme Court held in dis-l]\nmissing the mandamus brought by\nJohnston County school districts to j\nforce the board to supply the sched-j\nuled number of teachers, after a j\ncut, due to a reduced budget, had\nbeen made Tho potion of tho '-on-d!\nin that particular case was not sub\nject to control by mandamus, the\ncourt held. A compromise had pre\nviously been reached by the eduea-l\ntion board and the board of countv\ncommissioners, so the decision had\nno definite effect upon this much-]\ncontested Johnston County case-\nEight-Months School Term\ni A State-wide eight-months school\nterm for North Carolina, the last two\nmonths of which may be suspended)\nby the County Board of Education I\nj when the attendance will not justify I\njits continuation, is embraced in one]\nlof the two bills drawn up by the]\nspecial Educational Commission pro-!\nvuled by tho 1929 Legislature and\nto be submitted to the 1931 body)\nthrough Governor Gardner, just made|\npublic. In another hill, which the]\ncommission offers in case the Gen-i\neral Assembly is not ready to enact\nthe eight-months bill, are include F\ni provisions seeking to produce effi- j\ni ciency and economy, as are also in-1\neluded in the first hill.\nThe economy of operation is j\nsought through consolidation of ad\nministrative units, or school terms,!\nof spending agencies, and by greatc\nj aid front the State in current opera.-1\nj ing costs. Savings are expected\nI through suggested increase in teach-!\ner load, by abolishing the experience\ni increment in teacher salaries, and;\nin the administration of schools.\nThe bills seek to further eliminaf\nthe small school in favor of larger\nunits, permit the transfer of pupils\nacross district lines within the coun\nties and allow distribution of pup'ls\nto equalize the teaching load. The\ncommission, in its report, finds it]\n\u201cinadvisable at this time to create\nthe office of business manager or 1\nfinancial secretary for the State]\nj Board of Education,\u201d one of the oh-1\nj jects the commission was named to I\nj investigate and report on.\nCompletion of\nTax Round!\nI\nI will be at the following places on dates named\nfor the purpose of collecting the 1 930 taxes:\nSHAWNEEHAW TOWNSHIP\nTester\u2019s Store, November 17th, 10 a. m.\nLAUREL CREEK, November 18th\nJ. B. Hick\u2019s, A. M. Victor Ward\u2019s, P. M.\nBEAVER DAM, November 19th\nFarthing-Perry, A. M. Hagaman\u2019s Store, P. M.\nCOVE CREEK, November 20th\nZionville and Mabel, A. M. Silverstone, P. M.\nNovember 21st, Sherwood\u2019s, A. M.\nClyde Mast\u2019s Store, P. M.\nL. M. FARTHING\nSheriff Watauga County\nNOVEMBER 13, 1930\n421 Federal Number for\nBoone Trail Highway\nThe Boone Trail. N. C. No. 60.\nhas been given the federal number\n121 and signs have been placed on\nthe roadside hearing the number. In\n;i road meeting several months ago\nit was voted to give the road a fed\neral number hut the highway number\nigns were placed along the route\nduring the past few weeks.\nGiving the thoroughfare a federal\nnumber means that the road will be\nplaced on the map of federal cross\ncountry highways. Placing the route\non the federal map will no doubt\nhe the means of an increased tour\n\u25a0st traffic over the road through this\nsection- \u2014-Wilkes Journal.\n1 THE 1|\n1 SYLVIA I\ng SHOP\nEE SPECIALIZES IN\njg GIRLS\u2019 DRESSES\n(1 to 14-year Sizes)\nEE Broadcloth Jersey\nSerge or Silk\nWool Cashmere in\nPastel Shades\n1 NOTE:\nLovely pair BOUDOIR\nsr: SLIPPERS with largest\npurchase up to November .rr:\nlllllllllllllllllllllllillllllllllllllllllllll\nASTI ME\nTHEATRE\nof Good Shows\u201d\nFriday and Saturday, Nov 14-15\nBUCK JONES\nIn a Thrilling Western Picture\n\u201cSHADOW RANCH\u201d\nMonday and Tuesday, Nov. 17-18\nThe Marx Brothers\nANIMAL CRACKERS\u2019\nWednesday-Thursday, Nov. 19-20\nFifi Dorsay, Yola Davril\nSandra Ravel, Reginald\nDenny, Cliff Edwards\nIN\n\u201cTHOSE THREE\nFRENCH GIRLS\u201d\nMATINEES\nWEDNESDAYS AND SATURDAYS","height":"20191","width":"13818"}}
